vectorData.altText: 2) A child falls while climbing a fence and lacerates her axilla, damaging nerve A. Which movement (that you learned in Lab 14) would be most affected?

That's right!  This is the radial nerve, identifiable as it gives off the axillary nerve and then continues posterior to the shaft of the humerus. Damage to the radial nerve will affect elbow extension as the nerve innervates the triceps muscles of the posterior compartment of the arm.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.
The cords of the brachial plexus give rise to the major peripheral nerves of the upper limb.

Gently move the “M” aside, along with the axillary artery. Posterior to these structures find the terminal branches of the posterior cord of the brachial plexus, the radial (C5-T1) and axillary (C5-C6) nerves.
RETURN your attention to the axilla.

Follow the axillary nerve as it disappears posterior to the surgical neck of the humerus; it will be accompanied by the posterior circumflex humeral artery    . The target of the axillary nerve is the deltoid muscle, and the skin overlying the shoulder. Describe the motor and sensory deficits characteristic of a lesion of the axillary nerve. Think, then click! 
Follow the radial nerve as it disappears posterior to the humerus; it will be accompanied by the deep brachial artery     . It innervates, with no exception, the muscles of the posterior compartments of the arm and forearm, which are responsible for extension of the elbow, wrist and fingers, and the overlying skin.

weakness in abduction of the GH joint
sensory signs (pain, dysesthesia) in the skin overlying the shoulder

These pairing of a nerve with its companion artery are what I call “BFFs”; knowing that they always travel together (like Best Friends Forever) helps you to identify both the nerve and the artery! I will point out BFFs as we go along.
The axillary nerve and posterior circumflex humeral artery are BFFs!
the radial nerve and deep brachial artery are companions in the posterior compartment of the arm.
